.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,403,1366]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,435,547,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Material examined.</emphasis>
<specimenCount box="[445,616,547,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" type="generic">142 specimens</specimenCount>
; maximum size 
<quantity box="[806,909,547,574]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.09" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" unit="mm" value="30.9">30.9 mm</quantity>
length, 
<quantity box="[1004,1107,547,574]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8199999999999998" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" unit="mm" value="18.2">18.2 mm</quantity>
wide. N (n=22); D (n=8); 
<collectionCode box="[1420,1437,548,574]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">T</collectionCode>
(n=4); U (n=15); M (n=11); L (n=4); P (n=7); K (n=4); A (n=10), B (n=10); 
<collectionCode box="[997,1016,584,610]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">R</collectionCode>
(n=6); E (n=12); H (n=5); G (n=7); F (n=9); J (n=8); I (n=10).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,403,1366]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,580,655,681]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Habitat and bathymetric range.</emphasis>
This species can be found in a variety of habitats. Commonly adult animals (
<quantity box="[159,284,691,718]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" unit="mm" value="25.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="20.0">20–30 mm</quantity>
) occur in the shallow subtidal to 
<quantity box="[670,715,692,718]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" unit="m" value="7.0">7 m</quantity>
depth and on the underside of rocks buried in sand or covered with red and brown crustose algae. Juvenile specimens were usually found in the subtidal (
<quantity box="[1166,1252,727,754]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" unit="m" value="7.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="5.0">5–10 m</quantity>
depth) on shells or small stones, rarely on larger rocks. Adults are usually covered with bryozoans, polychaetes, and green or red algae that can also be attached to the girdle. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[654,884,799,825]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chaetopleuridae" genus="Chaetopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="lurida">
<emphasis box="[654,884,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Chaetopleura lurida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found together with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Broderip &amp; G. B. Sowerby I" authorityYear="1829" box="[1173,1395,799,825]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="albolineatus">
<emphasis box="[1173,1395,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Chiton albolineatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" authorityYear="1832" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="articulatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">C. articulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carpenter" authorityYear="1857" box="[287,463,835,861]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Tonicia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="forbesii">
<emphasis box="[287,463,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Tonicia forbesii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[523,783,835,861]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Ischnochitonidae" genus="Stenoplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="limaciformis">
<emphasis box="[523,783,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Stenoplax limaciformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="456" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,403,1366]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,871,897]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[323,553,871,897]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chaetopleuridae" genus="Chaetopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="lurida">
<emphasis box="[323,553,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Chaetopleura lurida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferreira" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[704,867,871,898]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chaetopleuridae" genus="Chaetopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hanselmani">
<emphasis box="[704,723,872,898]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[738,867,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">hanselmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of the pustules, which are somewhat cylindrical, and by having the double number of pustules. The maximum length recorded for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[1196,1297,907,934]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chaetopleuridae" genus="Chaetopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="lurida">
<emphasis box="[1196,1215,908,934]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1229,1297,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">lurida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<quantity box="[1330,1432,907,934]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.09" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" unit="mm" value="30.9">30.9 mm</quantity>
, while 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferreira" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[220,382,943,970]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chaetopleuridae" genus="Chaetopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hanselmani">
<emphasis box="[220,239,944,970]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[253,382,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">hanselmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can attain up to 
<quantity box="[568,670,943,970]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.18" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" unit="mm" value="11.8">11.8 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,403,1366]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">
The sculpturing pattern for this species has been reported to be highly variable (
<bibRefCitation author="Ferreira, A. J." box="[1114,1285,979,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" pagination="203 - 224" refId="ref20193" refString="Ferreira, A. J. (1983 a) The genus Chaetopleura Shuttleworth, 1853 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) in the warm temperate and tropical eastern Pacific, southern California to Peru, with the description of two new species. The Veliger, 25 (3), 203 - 224." type="journal article" year="1983">Ferreira 1983a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R." pageId="5" pageNumber="456" refId="ref21799" refString="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R. (1987) Monograph of Living Chitons (Mollusca: Polyplacophora). Vol. 3. Suborder Ischnochitonidae. Chaetopleurinae and Ischnochitoninae. Addition to Vols. 1 &amp; 2. E. J. Brill Backhuys, Leiden, 301 pp." type="book" year="1987">Kaas &amp; Van Belle 1987</bibRefCitation>
); regarding their observations, we also found morphologic distinctions in the sculpturing arrangement and color. The examination of 
<specimenCount box="[515,671,1051,1077]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" type="generic">31 specimens</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[747,973,1051,1077]" inferredBySuffix="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Baja California Sur</collectingRegion>
(e.g., specimen CNMO 1004 from 
<collectingCountry box="[1396,1436,1051,1077]" name="Iceland" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Isla</collectingCountry>
Partida; 
<figureCitation box="[244,332,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1746,1770]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-18@35.[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 20. Chiton articulatus, specimen BL 27 mm, El Faro, Mazatlán (CNMO 5661); shows the tegmentum color details A, head valve; B, intermediate valves III-V; C, tail valve. Specimen BL 24.45 mm, Santa Elena, Oaxaca (CNMO 1066); shows color tegmentum details; D, head valve; E, detail of intermediate valves III-V; F, tail valve. Chaetopleura lurida, G, dorsal view of whole specimen BL 21.3 x 13.7 mm, Estacahuite, Oaxaca (CNMO 5813). Chaetopleura lurida, specimen of 27.9 x 15.4 mm, dorsal view of valve I and IV, Isla Partida, Baja California Sur (CNMO 1004), H, head valve and I, valve IV; J, whole specimen BL 25.8 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit; K, Ischnochiton muscarius, whole specimen BL 27.6 mm in dorsal view.Callistochiton elenensis, L, whole specimen BL 19.46 mm, La Paz, Baja California Sur (UAGRO 0060); M, detail of sculpturing of valves II-IV; N, Chiton articulatus, N, whole specimen in dorsal view, BL 37.2 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit (CNMO 40012)." pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Fig. 20I</figureCitation>
) exhibited in general (from 26 examined chitons) pustules aligned more symmetrically in the lateral areas of intermediate valves, than the specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[764,865,1123,1149]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[920,1004,1123,1149]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
(southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1125,1212,1123,1150]" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">México</collectingCountry>
) that are irregularly scattered nearest the valve´s midline. Regarding the density of pustules, we observed that the chitons (
<specimenCount box="[1275,1428,1159,1186]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" type="generic">29 specimens</specimenCount>
) from Sayulita, 
<collectingRegion box="[322,406,1195,1221]" country="Mexico" name="Nayarit" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Nayarit</collectingRegion>
(e.g., CNMO 4651, 
<figureCitation box="[646,732,1195,1221]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1746,1770]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-18@35.[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 20. Chiton articulatus, specimen BL 27 mm, El Faro, Mazatlán (CNMO 5661); shows the tegmentum color details A, head valve; B, intermediate valves III-V; C, tail valve. Specimen BL 24.45 mm, Santa Elena, Oaxaca (CNMO 1066); shows color tegmentum details; D, head valve; E, detail of intermediate valves III-V; F, tail valve. Chaetopleura lurida, G, dorsal view of whole specimen BL 21.3 x 13.7 mm, Estacahuite, Oaxaca (CNMO 5813). Chaetopleura lurida, specimen of 27.9 x 15.4 mm, dorsal view of valve I and IV, Isla Partida, Baja California Sur (CNMO 1004), H, head valve and I, valve IV; J, whole specimen BL 25.8 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit; K, Ischnochiton muscarius, whole specimen BL 27.6 mm in dorsal view.Callistochiton elenensis, L, whole specimen BL 19.46 mm, La Paz, Baja California Sur (UAGRO 0060); M, detail of sculpturing of valves II-IV; N, Chiton articulatus, N, whole specimen in dorsal view, BL 37.2 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit (CNMO 40012)." pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Fig 20J</figureCitation>
) showed a higher number of pustule rows in the lateral areas (5–7) than those from 
<collectingRegion box="[398,499,1231,1257]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[552,636,1231,1257]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
(3–5). We also identified a latitudinal pattern of color variation: 
<collectingRegion box="[1352,1436,1231,1257]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
specimens (e.g., CNMO 5813, 
<figureCitation box="[497,597,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1746,1770]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-18@35.[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 20. Chiton articulatus, specimen BL 27 mm, El Faro, Mazatlán (CNMO 5661); shows the tegmentum color details A, head valve; B, intermediate valves III-V; C, tail valve. Specimen BL 24.45 mm, Santa Elena, Oaxaca (CNMO 1066); shows color tegmentum details; D, head valve; E, detail of intermediate valves III-V; F, tail valve. Chaetopleura lurida, G, dorsal view of whole specimen BL 21.3 x 13.7 mm, Estacahuite, Oaxaca (CNMO 5813). Chaetopleura lurida, specimen of 27.9 x 15.4 mm, dorsal view of valve I and IV, Isla Partida, Baja California Sur (CNMO 1004), H, head valve and I, valve IV; J, whole specimen BL 25.8 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit; K, Ischnochiton muscarius, whole specimen BL 27.6 mm in dorsal view.Callistochiton elenensis, L, whole specimen BL 19.46 mm, La Paz, Baja California Sur (UAGRO 0060); M, detail of sculpturing of valves II-IV; N, Chiton articulatus, N, whole specimen in dorsal view, BL 37.2 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit (CNMO 40012)." pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Fig. 20G</figureCitation>
) were usually brown, gray, or occasionally pink, while 
<collectingRegion box="[1212,1313,1267,1293]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
specimens were similar but had more areas with olive green coloration, whereas Mazatlán and 
<collectingRegion box="[1094,1312,1303,1329]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California Sur" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Baja California Sur</collectingRegion>
specimens usually had reddish-brown tones with dark zebra-like lines in the lateral areas.
</paragraph>
